english:
  title: Stele Commemorating Master Won, the First Great Teacher of Sugwang Bokwon Temple
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Emperor Wuzong of Yuan held faith in the Buddha's teachings and established a great temple south of the capital. Emperor Renzong continued his work and completed it in the first year of Huangqing. He commanded the finest monks from all regions to open the great hall and expound the dharma that winter. Master Won, a Yoga teacher from Goryeo, led his disciples to dwell there, remaining for twenty-nine years. In the second month of Gengchen year of Zhiyuan era, on the eighteenth day, he entered nirvana in the Hall of Perfect Sufficiency. Five years later, in the autumn of Jiashen year, his dharma heirs—Master Hyeongín and more than thirty other accomplished disciples—constructed a stupa to house his relics. They also sought to inscribe his deeds upon stone, and asked me to write this memorial, saying:

    "Life inevitably leads to death—this is the natural way. To nurture the living and honor the dead with proper respect is the sincere obligation of a son. The duty of a child to parents mirrors the duty of a disciple to a teacher. When Confucius passed away, his disciples mourned for three years, and some remained dwelling by his tomb, unable to depart. Though Confucius had successors, his followers acted thus. How much more should we monks, who renounce family ties and transmit the dharma as our lineage, honor the rites of final farewell? When the Buddha entered parinirvana, he lay upon his right side to show that there is an end; his relics were placed in a golden coffin to show that reverence was not withheld. Though the Buddha transcends the cycle of birth and death, his teachings of compassion and filial devotion remain woven throughout all things. Since our teacher passed, others entered the monastery, causing our community to scatter. Five years have now passed before we could finally enshrine his relics. This grief penetrates our very bones, and we cannot forget it for a single day. Write his memorial for us, that though our teacher has departed, something of him shall remain eternal."

    I had previously wandered between these master and disciples, so how could I refuse? Master Won's lay name was Haiwon, his family name Zhao, and he was from Hamnyeol. His father was Inspector of the Gate Guard and Grand General Yeok; his mother was the Lady Li of Wansan. From birth, the master was composed and dignified, his nature inherently kind and compassionate, his bearing unlike other children. His parents once said, "If this child does not become a great official, he shall surely become a great field of merit." At barely twelve years old, he took tonsure under Great Master Sekhong at Geumsan Temple and studied the dharma with such daily progress that none of his peers dared compare themselves to him. In spring of Giaogo year, he passed the Examination of the Buddhas and resided at Bulju Temple. In Dade year Eulsa, the Prince of Anxi heard that Goryeo monks maintained exceptional precepts and requested them from Emperor Chengzong. Master Won answered the call and entered the prince's service, accompanying him to the northern regions. The northern peoples did not farm but lived by herding, eating meat, drinking broth, and wearing hides. Though the master spent two winters and summers there, he endured hunger rather than break his vegetarian vows, his adherence to precepts only strengthening. The prince honored him all the more. In winter of Dingwei year, by Emperor Wuzong's decree, the master led his disciples, who were sustained by imperial granaries. During imperial tours each spring and autumn, he was commanded to attend the royal procession. When Emperor Renzong ascended the throne, he ordered the master to reside at this temple, and imperial favor and renown increased further. In the early Tianli era, twenty-five thousand sheets of paper currency were bestowed upon him as a mark of exceptional honor.

    The king of Goryeo showed him even greater respect. A memorial was submitted requesting that he preside over Geumsan Temple in Baekje from afar. He was granted the title "Great Master of Wisdom-Mirror, Perfect Illumination, Universal Light, Unobstructed, First of the Nation" and appointed as Great General Who Assists the Realm. His glory and light outshone all the sangha of his time. In his bearing, the master was broad-minded and harmonious; in his conduct, dignified and weighty. All who saw him felt affection and reverence. In his understanding of the Yogacara teachings, he had penetrated the essentials and never engaged in petty disputations with others—nor did others dare challenge him. He loved receiving guests without distinction of rank or character, treating all equally. His reception hall was always full. He expounded emptiness and existence with tireless diligence. His expenses often exceeded his income; the kitchen's supplies sometimes ran short, and his belongings grew sparse. When he passed away, he left nothing behind. He lived seventy-nine years. Truly, he was a field of merit indeed!

    I arrived in Gyeyu year of Yuantong era and stayed in Master Won's retreat at the Gratitude Temple. Thus I knew him well. Now upon my return, he has been gone more than a year, and his disciples have scattered to the four directions. I cannot help but grieve. I lament that those who study the Buddha's way still resort to seizing temples and feel no shame—their conduct is worse than worldly people. Yet now his disciples have recovered the monastery and, mourning the long delay in his funeral rites, have finally completed his stupa. Not only have they honored his legacy and repaid his kindness, but they have also elevated his virtues for perpetual transmission. This deserves to be inscribed in stone.

    The memorial says:

    Glorious is the benevolent Yuan,
    Surpassing Han and Tang in breadth.
    Following the ancients' example,
    Venerating the Buddha's truth.

    Bright the jeweled temple stands,
    Founded by Emperor Wuzong's hand,
    Perfected under Renzong's reign—
    All offerings fully prepared.

    Then came Master Won,
    Commanded to open the hall of dharma,
    Where the teaching broom swept flowers of rain,
    And heaven's fragrance clothed the robes.

    The master instructed his flock:
    "Never grow lazy or rough!
    With the people's labor spent,
    This sacred ground was built.

    When our granary flows with grain,
    Yet you tire of husks and bran—
    If you are but vessels of consumption,
    You are either foolish or mad."

    His disciples girded their robes,
    Daring not to fail their duty.
    At Chonggeun Bokwon for thirty years,
    Until he suddenly showed the world
    That even the enlightened taste impermanence.

    Countless were his finest heirs,
    Master Baek foremost among them.
    The temple found its anchor,
    The lineages their proper place.

    But those in darkness, knowing nothing,
    Dared seize the monastery's wealth.
    Yet heaven's wheel turns fair,
    And brought upon them calamity.

    The blue felt of tradition returns,
    The silk robes gleam anew,
    While the stupa stands tall and steadfast,
    His relics secured in shadow.

    The ground's fortune is firm and true,
    On the sunny side of the sacred realm.
    Though men say Buddhism transcends the bonds,
    Who knew his disciples would prove

    That they honor the departed,
    Repay his grace,
    And transmit his virtue to ages unborn?
    Let all future generations
    Behold this carved memorial.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Blue Felt (青氊) refers to the green blanket passed down through generations—a metaphor for the continuous transmission of Buddhist teaching and practice through successive generations of masters.
  - key: ''
    value: Master Baek (白) represents the ideal successor who properly maintains the temple and lineage, as opposed to the 'demons in darkness' who seized temples and caused destruction.
